Let's first recall, ***what is the Annual Percentage Rate?***

The Annual Percentage Rate $\operatorname{APR}$ is the interest generated in a year for a loan or an investment. It calculates de percentage of the principal a person will pay every year considering aspects like monthly payments but it does not include compounding. 

The $\operatorname{APR}$ method is used often used to determine the Money factor by dividing by $2,400$ when an interest rate is used by the car dealer.  Then:
$$
\begin{equation}
\text{Money factor} = \frac{\operatorname{APR}}{2400}   
\end{equation}
$$
If we clear $\operatorname{APR}$ from formula $(1)$, then:
$$
\begin{equation}
\operatorname{APR}= \text{Money factor}\times{2400}   
\end{equation}
$$

Another way of calculating the $\operatorname{APR}$ is by multiplying the **periodic interest rate** by the **number of periods in the year that is been applied**.

***What are monthly lease payments?***

Monthly lease payments are equivalent to monthly rent. Is the payment per month a lessee gives to the owner of a good this subject is renting, for example, an apartment, a car, and many other assets. 

To determine the monthly lease payments we have to determine three factors: 
- a depreciation fee, 
- a finance fee, and; 
- sales tax.

From exercise indications we can establish to calculate monthly payment by the following formula:

$$
\begin{equation}
\text{Monthly payment}= \text{Depreciation fee}+\text{Sales tax} 
\end{equation}
$$

To determine these three factors we have formulas $(4)$ to $(7)$: 
$$
\begin{equation}
\text{Depreciation fee} = \frac{\text{Net capitalization costs} – \text{residual value}}{ \text{Term of the lease}}    
\end{equation}
$$

Where: 
$$
\begin{equation}
\text{Net capitalization cost} = \small\text{Capitalization cost} – 
\small\text{cost reduction} + 
\small\text{additional costs}    
\end{equation}
$$

$$
\begin{equation}
\text{Finance fee} = (\text{Net capitalization cost} + \text{residual cost})\times \text{Money factor}    
\end{equation}
$$ 

$$
\begin{equation}
\text{Sales tax} = (\text{Depreciation payment} + \text{Finance fee}) \times\text{Tax rate}    
\end{equation}
$$

So, let's calculate together!

Let's now calculate the three factors of the monthly payment:
$$
\begin{align*}
\text{Depreciation fee} = \frac{(\text{Net capitalization costs } – \text{ residual value})}{\text{Term of the lease}}   
\end{align*}
$$
If we substitute formula $(5)$ into formula $(4)$ we have:
$$
 \begin{align*}
\text{Depreciation fee} &= \frac{\small{(\text{Capitalization cost } – \text{ cost reduction} + \text{additional costs} – \text{residual value})}}{\text{Term of the lease}}\\[10pt]
&= \frac{(\$41,900 + \$850 -\$4,300 - \$30,500)}{36}\\[10pt]
&= \frac{\$7,950}{36}\\[10pt] 
&= \$220.83
\end{align*}
$$

***The Depreciation fee per month is $\bold{\$220.83}$.***
